The start symbol S can expand only in one of three ways:

1. S → NT33 NT37  
2. S → NT21 NT34  
3. S → NT14 NT2  

The string begins with the terminal t12.  
To see whether any of these three possibilities can yield t12 as the first symbol, examine what each left‑hand component (NT33, NT21, NT14) can ultimately produce as its very first terminal.

• NT14 is a lexical non‑terminal; its only terminals are t46, t15, t23 and t32 – never t12.  
  → Expansion 3 is impossible.

• NT33 can begin with one of:
  – a direct terminal (t31, t13, t0, t39, t6, t35) – none is t12;  
  – NT30 … (first terminals t47, t60, t59, t3, t21, t11, t53);  
  – NT1 … (first terminals t19, t10, t18, or further expansions, none of which can yield t12 as the first symbol);  
  – NT9 … (first terminals t24, or via NT31 etc., again never t12).  
  → Expansion 1 cannot give t12 as the first symbol.

• NT21 can start with
  – a direct terminal (t50, t27, t3, t34) – not t12, or  
  – NT26 NT5, NT15 NT31, NT8 NT37.  
  Only NT15 derives t12 directly (NT15 → 't12'), so S → NT21 NT34 requires the sequence  
     S ⇒ NT21 NT34 ⇒ NT15 NT31 NT34 ⇒ t12 …  
  giving the desired first symbol.

Now check the remainder of the string.  After NT15 has supplied the initial t12, the rest of the string (44 more tokens) must be produced by NT31 NT34, with NT34 contributing the final block.

NT34, however, can produce only  
  – a single terminal (t58, t38, or t56), or  
  – two components NT14 NT25 whose first terminal must be one of t46, t15, t23 or t32.  

The given 44‑token tail ends with “… t40 t11”.  None of the single‑terminal options matches that suffix, and the two‑component option would force the next token after NT31 to be one of t46, t15, t23, t32, which never occurs in the required position.  Therefore NT31 NT34 cannot generate the remaining 44 tokens.

Since the only viable top‑level expansion of S fails to match the rest of the string, the string is not in the language of the grammar.
